Die Verlierer bleiben Herausforderer
HARARE: Vor den Präsidentschaftswahlen in diesem Monat war ich überzeugt davon, dass Unregelmäßigkeiten bei den Wahlen ernsthafte Konsequenzen in Simbabwe selbst und im ganzen südlichen Afrika hätten.
Trotz der Schatten von Krieg und Terrorismus rief ich zu fairen und freien Wahlen auf.
Die Menschen von Simbabwe haben sie nicht bekommen.
Stattdessen haben sie Terror erhalten.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the Zimbabwe African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is accounted for by the gang elements among the veterans from Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men all of whom are supported by the police.
Owing to intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), was unable to reach the electorate in large parts, especially in rural areas.
Moreover, my opponent's, President Mugabe's, government disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and Chitungwiza.
Given that there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion more than 360,000 people stood in line alone in Harare and Chitungwiza without being able to cast their ballot.
I still doubt the legitimacy of the election result because Mugabe's militias prevented MDC observers from being present at 52% of rural polling stations.
Towards the end of voting, our party observers were missing from 6 out of 10 polling stations in rural areas.
This means that Mugabe's supporters could impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, even at this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most votes went to Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of Zimbabwe's people and is considered illegitimate by them.
The people of Zimbabwe were denied their right to freely and democratically elect their president.
The fight over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation exceeds 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and they deserve to have this acknowledged.
Perhaps it is not too late for that.
I write these words in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand as a faithful servant with the people and go the whole way with them.
Possibly the government wants to arrest me.
I were also already arrested for high treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government can never break the will of the people to assert their rights and power.
It lies in our hands to bring about a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
The political change is irreversible.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his thugs fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I only ask the people of Zimbabwe to stay strong and finish what we have begun together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who were not driven away.
These are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe whose voices must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very steep path together to bring about a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to maintain kindness and enthusiasm.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But for a political process to take place, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply ignore these elections, but they must also not fall for Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that elections are rigged across Africa.
In most African states, irregularities, fraud, and deception at elections seem to be par for the course.
There is always some kind of crisis regarding elections in Africa.
It is sad, but the whole continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it comes time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something different can hope.
imbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
Noch ist Zeit, aus unserer Erfahrung die Lehren für Afrika und die Welt zu ziehen.
Mein Volk ist in der Stunde seiner größten Not.
Ich gelobe, es nicht zu verlassen.
